    "note": " Serum amylase is usually elevated within a few hours to levels higher than 1000 IU/dL (normal value is 100-300 IU/dL). It remains elevated for 2-3 days only. The problem with serum amylase is that it is not specific for acute pancreatitis. It is elevated in other conditions as perforated peptic ulcer, acute cholecystitis, intestinal obstruction and acute mesenteric ischaemia. The enzyme level in these cases, however, usually does not exceed 500 IU/dL. As this enzyme is cleared out by the kidney, urinary amylase level can be used for diagnosis of patients who present after two days of the start of pain. Pancreatic necrosis is diagnosed when a big part of the parenchyma is not enhanced after IV contrast injection. The presence of necrosis is a strong indicator of severity of the attack. A CT scan should be performed at least 48 hours after the onset of symptoms in order to detect the extent of necrosis.",
